  <Subject Subject_ID="300041839">
    <Parent_Relationships>
      <Preferred_Parent>
        <Parent_Subject_ID>300198349</Parent_Subject_ID>
        <Relationship_Type>Parent/Child</Relationship_Type>
        <Historic_Flag>Current</Historic_Flag>
        <Parent_String>tubular drums with single head [300198349], tubular drums [300194009], struck drums [300041669], drums (membranophones) [300041729], membranophones [300041661], sound devices by acoustical characteristics [300041621], sound devices (equipment) [300387677], Sound Devices (hierarchy name) [300041619], Furnishings and Equipment (hierarchy name) [300264551], Objects Facet [300264092]</Parent_String>
        <Hier_Rel_Type>Genus/Species-BTG</Hier_Rel_Type>
      </Preferred_Parent>
    </Parent_Relationships>
    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Small single-headed drums, Afro-Cuban in origin, with conical or cylindrical hardwood shells; they generally occur in pairs joined together horizontally, one being larger in diameter than the other. Existing in tunable and nontunable versions, they are played with the bare hands.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000099620/Legacy AAT data</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Pequeños tambores de una sola cabeza, de origen afrocubano, con conchas cónicas o cilíndricas de madera dura; generalmente se usan en pares unidos juntos en forma horizontal, siendo uno más grande en diámetro que el otro. Existen en versiones posibles de afinar y otras que no se pueden afinar, y se tocan sólo con las manos.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Spanish</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000131/CDBP-SNPC</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000051034/TAA database (2000-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Afro-Cubaanse hardhouten cilindertrommels, soms kegelvormig, wel of niet stembaar en met de hand bespeeld; meestal in paren, horizontaal aan elkaar vastgemaakt, waarbij de ene trom een grotere doorsnede heeft dan de andere.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000113770/AAT-Ned (1994-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000052453/Algemene muziekencyclopedie (1961)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>源於古巴黑人音樂的小型單面鼓，具有圓錐狀或圓柱狀的硬木鼓身，通常成對水平並置，其中一個鼓的直徑較大，分為可調音式和不可調音式，以徒手演奏。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000250/AS-Academia Sinica</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000052784/TELDAP database (2009-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Pequenos tambores de cabeça única, de origem afro-cubana, com conchas cônicas ou cilíndricas de madeira de lei; eles geralmente ocorrem em pares unidos horizontalmente, sendo um maior em diâmetro que o outro. Existentes em versões sintonizáveis ​​e não sintonizáveis, são tocadas com as próprias mãos.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Portuguese</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000316/CVAA-BR</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000109633/CVAA-BR Consortium (2020-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Kleine, einfellige Trommel afro-kubanischen Ursprungs mit konischem oder zylindrischem Korpus aus Hartholz; sie wird gewöhnlich paarweise verwendet, wobei die beiden Trommeln horizontal miteinander verbunden sind, eine größer im Durchmesser als die andere. Es gibt sie in stimmbarer und nicht-stimmbarer Ausführung, und sie wird mit den bloßen Händen gespielt.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>German</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000232/IfM-SMB-PK</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000122134/IfM Berlin</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
    </Descriptive_Notes>
